00:46:42.720 --> 00:46:44.550
The second question
of the responsibility

00:46:44.550 --> 00:46:47.790
of platforms to make sure that
social media and the internet

00:46:47.790 --> 00:46:51.870
is a force for good
as opposed to a force

00:46:51.870 --> 00:46:55.800
that it elects the 45th
president of the United States

00:46:55.800 --> 00:47:01.140
is, I think, one of the
most significant questions

00:47:01.140 --> 00:47:02.580
before us.

00:47:02.580 --> 00:47:08.640
How do we leverage changing
and advancing technologies

00:47:08.640 --> 00:47:10.360
for good and not for ill?

00:47:10.360 --> 00:47:14.270
How do we address
the reality also

00:47:14.270 --> 00:47:17.330
that in this individualized
media society,

00:47:17.330 --> 00:47:20.870
half of the country is truly
not even hearing the other half?

00:47:20.870 --> 00:47:23.280
How do we bridge that divide,
whether it's in cable news,

00:47:23.280 --> 00:47:25.670
whether it's on
Facebook, whether it's

00:47:25.670 --> 00:47:27.530
on social media,
where people are

00:47:27.530 --> 00:47:29.600
going into these echo chambers?

00:47:29.600 --> 00:47:32.270
And if you're going into
an echo chamber of hate,

00:47:32.270 --> 00:47:35.570
it emboldens your hate.

00:47:35.570 --> 00:47:37.190
I don't have a good answer.

00:47:37.190 --> 00:47:39.980
That's, honestly,
above my pay grade

00:47:39.980 --> 00:47:44.540
in terms of what
are the mechanisms

00:47:44.540 --> 00:47:48.455
that these individual
platforms should utilize

00:47:48.455 --> 00:47:50.330
or what steps should
they take to address it.

00:47:50.330 --> 00:47:55.160
I do think they have a
moral obligation, a business

00:47:55.160 --> 00:47:58.670
obligation, and a
practical obligation

00:47:58.670 --> 00:48:02.790
to make sure that they are truly
rooting out hate speech when

00:48:02.790 --> 00:48:05.090
it occurs and
violent speech when

00:48:05.090 --> 00:48:06.410
it occurs on their platforms.

00:48:06.410 --> 00:48:07.785
If they have these
policies, they

00:48:07.785 --> 00:48:10.010
need to actually abide by them.

00:48:10.010 --> 00:48:14.397
I think they need to make
sure that if they don't

00:48:14.397 --> 00:48:15.980
have those policies,
they are adopting

00:48:15.980 --> 00:48:18.590
those policies, for one.

00:48:18.590 --> 00:48:20.750
I think one of the
exciting things that we're

00:48:20.750 --> 00:48:24.160
seeing right now is that the
generation just behind me--

00:48:24.160 --> 00:48:27.290
I'm a millennial-- the
generation that are

00:48:27.290 --> 00:48:30.466
digital natives are doing it.

00:48:30.466 --> 00:48:32.340
I don't think they know
how they're doing it,

00:48:32.340 --> 00:48:33.470
but I think they're
already doing it

00:48:33.470 --> 00:48:35.094
where they're bridging
that divide that

00:48:35.094 --> 00:48:40.910
exists across media, and
they're utilizing social media

00:48:40.910 --> 00:48:43.430
for good.

00:48:43.430 --> 00:48:46.250
And I think that's going to
be the generation that truly

00:48:46.250 --> 00:48:50.120
figures out how we
solve what feels almost

00:48:50.120 --> 00:48:52.460
like an unsolvable
problem at this point.

00:48:52.460 --> 00:48:53.960
I know the obligations
exist, but I

00:48:53.960 --> 00:48:56.270
don't have answers for them.

00:48:56.270 --> 00:48:58.700
And I would certainly
charge anyone

00:48:58.700 --> 00:49:02.030
who's working in tech
to actively grapple

00:49:02.030 --> 00:49:04.010
with these questions,
to actively grapple

00:49:04.010 --> 00:49:06.950
with the policies you have
and the practices that

